{
  "executive_summary": "Decompose the courier platform monolith into 6 bounded services aligned with domain boundaries: Order, Courier, Location Tracking, Notification, Payment, and Customer Account. The decomposition prioritizes the stated goal of deployment decoupling while respecting the team's moderate operational maturity — recommending a phased strangler-fig migration rather than a big-bang rewrite. Location Tracking is extracted first as it has the highest write volume (5K writes/sec), the most distinct scaling profile, and the lowest domain coupling to payment consistency concerns.",

  "architecture": {
    "components": [
      {
        "name": "Order Service",
        "responsibility": "Order lifecycle management: placement, status transitions, cancellation. Owns the order aggregate and orchestrates cross-service workflows (courier assignment, payment capture) via events.",
        "boundaries": "Owns order data. Does NOT own courier state, payment state, or customer profile. Publishes OrderPlaced, OrderCancelled, OrderDelivered events."
      },
      {
        "name": "Courier Service",
        "responsibility": "Courier onboarding, availability management, assignment algorithm, and route optimization. Owns courier profile and assignment state.",
        "boundaries": "Owns courier profiles and assignment logic. Consumes location data from Location Tracking via events but does NOT own raw location storage. Publishes CourierAssigned, CourierUnassigned events."
      },
      {
        "name": "Location Tracking Service",
        "responsibility": "Ingests real-time GPS updates from courier devices (5K writes/sec peak), stores time-series location data, exposes current-position queries and location history.",
        "boundaries": "Owns all raw location data. Write-optimized store (time-series DB). Publishes LocationUpdated events for downstream consumers. No business logic beyond geofencing — assignment decisions live in Courier Service."
      },
      {
        "name": "Notification Service",
        "responsibility": "Fan-out of customer-facing notifications across channels (email, SMS, push). Template management. Delivery tracking and retry.",
        "boundaries": "Owns notification templates and delivery state. Stateless with respect to business domain — reacts to events from other services. No domain logic."
      },
      {
        "name": "Payment Service",
        "responsibility": "Payment authorization, capture, refund processing. Integration with payment gateway(s). Ledger of financial transactions with strict consistency.",
        "boundaries": "Owns all financial records. Synchronous API for payment operations (consistency requirement). Publishes PaymentCaptured, RefundIssued events. ACID transactions internally — no eventual consistency on money."
      },
      {
        "name": "Customer Account Service",
        "responsibility": "Customer registration, authentication, profile management, address book, preferences.",
        "boundaries": "Owns customer identity and profile data. Other services reference customers by ID only. Publishes CustomerCreated, CustomerUpdated events."
      }
    ],
    "interfaces": [
      {
        "from": "Order Service",
        "to": "Courier Service",
        "contract": "Async event: OrderPlaced → triggers courier assignment. Courier Service publishes CourierAssigned back.",
        "coupling_type": "event-driven (loose)"
      },
      {
        "from": "Order Service",
        "to": "Payment Service",
        "contract": "Sync RPC: AuthorizePayment(orderId, amount, paymentMethod) → returns authorization token. CapturePayment on delivery confirmation. This is synchronous because order placement must fail if payment authorization fails.",
        "coupling_type": "synchronous RPC (tight, intentional)"
      },
      {
        "from": "Courier Service",
        "to": "Location Tracking Service",
        "contract": "Query API: GetCurrentLocation(courierId). Subscribe to LocationUpdated events for proximity-based assignment.",
        "coupling_type": "event-driven + read API (loose)"
      },
      {
        "from": "Order Service",
        "to": "Notification Service",
        "contract": "Async event: OrderStatusChanged → Notification Service renders and sends appropriate notification per channel.",
        "coupling_type": "event-driven (loose)"
      },
      {
        "from": "Location Tracking Service",
        "to": "Notification Service",
        "contract": "Async event: CourierNearby (geofence trigger) → push notification to customer.",
        "coupling_type": "event-driven (loose)"
      },
      {
        "from": "Order Service",
        "to": "Customer Account Service",
        "contract": "Read API: GetCustomer(customerId) for order validation. Cached locally with short TTL.",
        "coupling_type": "synchronous read with cache (moderate)"
      }
    ],
    "data_flow": "Courier devices → Location Tracking Service (high-throughput ingest via UDP/WebSocket) → publishes LocationUpdated to message broker → consumed by Courier Service (for assignment) and Notification Service (for geofence alerts). Customer places order → Order Service validates via Customer Account Service, authorizes payment synchronously via Payment Service, publishes OrderPlaced → Courier Service assigns courier and publishes CourierAssigned → Order Service updates status → Notification Service sends updates. On delivery: Order Service captures payment synchronously, publishes OrderDelivered → all downstream consumers react.",
    "patterns_used": [
      {
        "pattern": "Strangler Fig Migration",
        "rationale": "Team has 3 years of monolith experience and moderate ops maturity. Big-bang rewrite is high risk. Extract services incrementally behind a facade, starting with Location Tracking (highest scaling pressure, lowest domain coupling)."
      },
      {
        "pattern": "Event-Driven Architecture (via message broker)",
        "rationale": "Achieves the stated goal of deployment decoupling. Services communicate through domain events, eliminating runtime coupling for most interactions. Only Payment requires synchronous calls due to consistency requirements."
      },
      {
        "pattern": "CQRS (Location Tracking only)",
        "rationale": "Location Tracking has a 50:1 write-to-read ratio at peak. Separating the write path (time-series ingest) from the read path (current position queries) allows independent scaling. Not applied globally — would add unnecessary complexity for other services."
      },
      {
        "pattern": "Database-per-Service",
        "rationale": "Each service owns its data store. This is non-negotiable for deployment decoupling — shared databases are the #1 source of hidden coupling in failed microservice migrations."
      },
      {
        "pattern": "Saga (Choreography-based)",
        "rationale": "Order placement spans Order, Payment, and Courier services. Use choreography-based sagas (event chains) rather than orchestration to avoid a central coordinator bottleneck. Compensating actions handle failures (e.g., release payment hold if no courier available)."
      }
    ]
  },

  "domain_model": {
    "bounded_contexts": [
      {
        "name": "Order Management",
        "classification": "core",
        "aggregates": ["Order (root: orderId, contains line items, delivery address, status)"]
      },
      {
        "name": "Courier Operations",
        "classification": "core",
        "aggregates": ["Courier (root: courierId, contains availability, current assignment)", "Assignment (root: assignmentId, links order to courier)"]
      },
      {
        "name": "Location Tracking",
        "classification": "supporting",
        "aggregates": ["CourierLocation (root: courierId, append-only location entries — modeled as time-series, not traditional aggregate)"]
      },
      {
        "name": "Payments",
        "classification": "core",
        "aggregates": ["PaymentTransaction (root: transactionId, contains authorization, captures, refunds — strict consistency)"]
      },
      {
        "name": "Notifications",
        "classification": "generic",
        "aggregates": ["NotificationTemplate", "DeliveryRecord"]
      },
      {
        "name": "Customer Identity",
        "classification": "supporting",
        "aggregates": ["Customer (root: customerId, contains profile, addresses, preferences)"]
      }
    ],
    "context_map": [
      {
        "upstream": "Order Management",
        "downstream": "Courier Operations",
        "relationship": "Customer-Supplier — Order defines what needs delivery, Courier Operations conforms to order's delivery requirements"
      },
      {
        "upstream": "Order Management",
        "downstream": "Notifications",
        "relationship": "Customer-Supplier — Notifications is a generic consumer, conforms to Order's event schema"
      },
      {
        "upstream": "Location Tracking",
        "downstream": "Courier Operations",
        "relationship": "Open Host Service — Location Tracking exposes a published language (lat/lng/timestamp) that Courier Operations consumes for assignment decisions"
      },
      {
        "upstream": "Order Management",
        "downstream": "Payments",
        "relationship": "Customer-Supplier with ACL — Payment Service has its own financial model; an Anti-Corruption Layer translates between order concepts and payment concepts"
      },
      {
        "upstream": "Customer Identity",
        "downstream": "Order Management",
        "relationship": "Conformist — Order stores customerId reference and caches minimal customer data; conforms to Customer Identity's model"
      }
    ]
  },

  "trade_offs": [
    {
      "decision": "Synchronous RPC for Payment authorization during order placement",
      "gains": "Strong consistency — order never enters system without valid payment authorization. No orphaned orders. Simpler failure handling.",
      "sacrifices": "Runtime coupling between Order and Payment services. Payment outage blocks order placement. Higher latency on order creation.",
      "alternatives_considered": ["Async payment with reservation pattern — rejected because partial failures create orphaned orders that need complex reconciliation", "Two-phase commit — rejected as impractical across service boundaries"]
    },
    {
      "decision": "Choreography-based sagas over orchestration",
      "gains": "No central orchestrator to become a bottleneck or single point of failure. Each service owns its reactions. Simpler to reason about locally.",
      "sacrifices": "Harder to visualize end-to-end flow. Debugging distributed workflows requires correlation IDs and distributed tracing. Can become tangled if saga steps exceed 4-5.",
      "alternatives_considered": ["Orchestrator service (e.g., Order Saga Orchestrator) — viable for more complex flows but adds operational overhead for an 8-person team"]
    },
    {
      "decision": "Time-series database for Location Tracking (e.g., TimescaleDB, InfluxDB)",
      "gains": "Purpose-built for 5K writes/sec of append-only geo-temporal data. Efficient retention policies. Compression optimized for time-series.",
      "sacrifices": "Introduces a new database technology the team may not have operated before. Adds operational surface area.",
      "alternatives_considered": ["PostgreSQL with partitioning — viable up to ~10K writes/sec but requires careful partition management", "Redis Streams — good for hot data but poor for historical queries"]
    },
    {
      "decision": "6 services for 8 engineers",
      "gains": "Clean domain boundaries. Each service can be owned by 1-2 engineers. Achieves deployment decoupling goal.",
      "sacrifices": "Ratio of ~1.3 engineers per service is tight. On-call rotation will be thin. Cross-cutting changes still require coordination.",
      "alternatives_considered": ["Fewer services (merge Courier + Location Tracking) — rejected because their scaling profiles are fundamentally different (Location is write-heavy infra, Courier is business logic)", "More granular services — rejected as the team is too small to sustain more than 6"]
    }
  ],

  "flexibility_points": [
    {
      "area": "Notification channels",
      "evolution_path": "Notification Service is generic and channel-agnostic. Adding WhatsApp, in-app messaging, or webhook channels requires zero changes to upstream services — just add a new channel adapter."
    },
    {
      "area": "Courier assignment algorithm",
      "evolution_path": "Assignment logic is encapsulated in Courier Service. Can evolve from simple nearest-courier to ML-based optimization without touching Order Service or Location Tracking."
    },
    {
      "area": "Location Tracking throughput",
      "evolution_path": "Isolated behind its own API and data store. Can scale write path independently (horizontal partitioning by courier region) without affecting other services."
    },
    {
      "area": "Payment providers",
      "evolution_path": "Payment Service's ACL isolates payment gateway specifics. Can swap Stripe for Adyen or add multi-provider routing without touching Order Service."
    }
  ],

  "rigidity_points": [
    {
      "area": "Order-Payment synchronous coupling",
      "reason": "Intentionally rigid. Payment authorization MUST succeed before order is accepted. This coupling reflects a real business invariant — weakening it creates financial risk."
    },
    {
      "area": "Event schema contracts",
      "reason": "Once services depend on event schemas (OrderPlaced, CourierAssigned, etc.), schema evolution requires backward compatibility. Must version events from day one."
    },
    {
      "area": "Customer ID as cross-service reference",
      "reason": "All services reference customers by customerId. Changing the identity scheme would require coordinated migration across all services."
    }
  ],

  "risks": [
    {
      "risk": "Operational maturity gap — team has run a monolith for 3 years and now must operate 6 services, a message broker, distributed tracing, and per-service databases",
      "severity": "critical",
      "mitigation": "Phased migration via strangler fig. Extract Location Tracking first (most isolated, highest scaling benefit). Invest in observability (distributed tracing, centralized logging, health dashboards) BEFORE extracting the second service. Do not extract more than one service per quarter."
    },
    {
      "risk": "Distributed transaction failures in the order placement saga (payment authorized but courier assignment fails)",
      "severity": "high",
      "mitigation": "Implement compensating actions: if courier assignment fails within timeout, release payment authorization and notify customer. Use correlation IDs to trace saga state. Add a dead-letter queue for failed events with alerting."
    },
    {
      "risk": "Data consistency during migration — monolith and new services must coexist during strangler fig transition",
      "severity": "high",
      "mitigation": "Use change data capture (CDC) to sync data between monolith and extracted services during transition. Define clear cutover criteria for each service extraction. Never run dual-write — it's a consistency nightmare."
    },
    {
      "risk": "Location Tracking data volume — 5K writes/sec × 86,400 sec/day = ~432M records/day before compression",
      "severity": "medium",
      "mitigation": "Implement retention policies from day one: full resolution for 24 hours, downsampled (1-min intervals) for 30 days, aggregated daily summaries for historical. Time-series DB handles this natively."
    },
    {
      "risk": "Team cognitive load — 8 engineers learning microservice patterns (event sourcing, sagas, CQRS) while maintaining production monolith",
      "severity": "medium",
      "mitigation": "Apply CQRS only to Location Tracking where the read/write asymmetry justifies it. Use choreography sagas (simpler than orchestration). Avoid event sourcing entirely — it's not needed here and would compound the learning curve."
    }
  ],

  "implementation_guidance": {
    "recommended_approach": "Phased strangler fig migration in 4 stages. Phase 1 (Q1): Extract Location Tracking Service — it has the highest scaling pressure, lowest domain coupling, and gives the team microservice operational experience with minimal business risk. Phase 2 (Q2): Extract Notification Service — generic, stateless, low-risk extraction that validates the event-driven architecture. Phase 3 (Q3): Extract Payment Service — high business criticality but well-bounded; requires careful testing of synchronous RPC and consistency guarantees. Phase 4 (Q4): Extract Courier, Order, and Customer Account services — these are the most tightly coupled in the monolith and should be separated last, once the team has operational confidence. Invest in shared infrastructure (message broker, distributed tracing, CI/CD per service) before Phase 1.",
    "files_to_create_or_modify": [
      "infrastructure/docker-compose.yml — local dev environment with message broker (Kafka or RabbitMQ), per-service databases",
      "services/location-tracking/ — first service to extract: ingest API, time-series store, event publisher",
      "services/location-tracking/proto/location.proto — gRPC/protobuf contract for location updates (high throughput path)",
      "shared/events/schemas/ — versioned event schema definitions (Avro or JSON Schema) for cross-service contracts",
      "shared/observability/ — distributed tracing configuration, correlation ID middleware, structured logging standards",
      "docs/adr/001-microservice-decomposition.md — Architecture Decision Record documenting this decomposition and rationale",
      "docs/adr/002-event-schema-versioning.md — ADR for event versioning strategy (backward compatible evolution)",
      "docs/runbooks/ — per-service operational runbooks (required before each service goes to production)"
    ],
    "patterns_to_follow": "Database-per-service (non-negotiable). Event-driven communication as default, synchronous RPC only where consistency demands it (Payment). Strangler fig for migration. CQRS only for Location Tracking. Choreography sagas for multi-service workflows. API Gateway for external clients. Correlation IDs on every request and event.",
    "pitfalls_to_avoid": [
      "Shared database between services — this is the single most common microservice anti-pattern and defeats the entire purpose of decomposition",
      "Extracting too many services at once — the team must build operational muscle incrementally; extracting 6 services simultaneously will overwhelm an 8-person team",
      "Synchronous call chains (A calls B calls C calls D) — design for async events; synchronous coupling should be point-to-point only (Order→Payment)",
      "Skipping observability investment — you cannot debug distributed systems with monolith-era logging; distributed tracing and centralized logging are prerequisites, not nice-to-haves",
      "Dual-write during migration — never write to both monolith DB and new service DB in the same code path; use CDC or event-based sync",
      "Event sourcing — the team does not need it and the learning curve will slow delivery; standard event-driven architecture with a message broker is sufficient"
    ]
  },

  "escalations": [],

  "confidence": {
    "level": 82,
    "high_confidence_areas": [
      "Service boundaries align cleanly with domain boundaries — these are natural seams",
      "Location Tracking extraction as Phase 1 — clearly the right first move given scaling profile and low coupling",
      "Synchronous Payment coupling is the correct trade-off for financial consistency",
      "6 services is the right granularity for 8 engineers"
    ],
    "low_confidence_areas": [
      "Choreography vs orchestration for sagas — choreography is recommended for simplicity but if the order flow grows more complex (multi-stop, scheduled delivery, etc.), orchestration may become necessary",
      "Message broker choice (Kafka vs RabbitMQ) — depends on team familiarity and whether event replay is valued; not enough info to recommend one",
      "Exact timeline for 4-phase migration — depends on team velocity and current monolith coupling which I cannot assess without seeing the codebase"
    ],
    "assumptions": [
      "The monolith is a single deployable unit with a shared database",
      "The 500 active couriers figure represents typical load, not peak — peak courier count may be higher",
      "The team has basic containerization experience (Docker) but has not operated a distributed system in production",
      "There is no existing message broker or event infrastructure in the monolith"
    ]
  }
}

